Reasoning: The paper deals with diagnostic imaging and the use of machine learning to improve the accuracy of medical diagnosis. The approach involves the use of multiple resolutions and weak supervision to generate saliency maps for localizing abnormalities. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the use of a novel architecture and the parameterization of the Log-Sum-Exp pooling function with a learnable lower-bounded adaptation suggest that the paper may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The use of medical training data and the focus on chest x-rays suggest that the paper may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the use of natural language processing techniques to augment clinical workflow suggests that the paper may also belong to the computational linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category.
